Submandibular duct stone","Dental abscess","Salivary gland pleomorphic adenoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe intermittent nature of the swelling would fit well for transient duct obstruction. The site and timing of the swelling in relation to meals are virtually diagnostic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Esubmandibular duct calculus\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnatomically, a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebranchial cyst\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroglossal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E may be excluded. Thyroglossal cysts are a midline structure, due to the location of the embryological thyroglossal duct. Branchial cysts vary in location depending on the branchial cleft from which they arise, but are typically found along the course of the sternocleidomastoid and may be obscured deep to the muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleomorphic adenomas\u003C/strong\u003E affect the parotid gland much more commonly than the submandibular gland - thus, the location of this mass would be less suspicious for this type of malignancy. Furthermore, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E would not fluctuate in size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edental abscess\u003C/strong\u003E may cause submandibular swelling, particularly when the abscess arises from the root of the second or third molars. However, a dental abscess is very unlikely to be painless, would be unlikely to fluctuate in size, and is often associated with mild trismus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intermittent swelling of the submandibular gland after meals is almost certainly due to a stone in the duct."],"references":["Kraaij S, Karagozoglu KH, Forouzanfar T, Veerman EC, Brand HS. Salivary stones: symptoms, aetiology, biochemical composition and treatment. Br Dent J. 2014 Dec 5;217(11):E23. doi: 10.1038/sj.bdj.2014.1054. PMID: 25476659."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{